          <div class="field-item">  <div class="paragraph paragraph--type--prize-fellowship-recipient paragraph--view-mode--default">
                        <a class=" meghan-o’rourke" name="meghan-o’rourke"></a>
        <div id="meghan-o’rourke" class="content-section">
    
          
          <a href="/person/meghan-orourke"><div class="prize-fellowship-recipient__name prize-fellowship-recipient__name--default field field-paragraph--field-title-plain field-name-field-title-plain field-type-string field-label-hidden">
    <div class="field-items">
          <div class="field-item">Meghan O’Rourke</div>
      </div>
</div>
</a>
        <div class="prize-fellowship-recipient__year prize-fellowship-recipient__year--default field field-paragraph--field-year field-name-field-year field-type-string field-label-hidden">
    <div class="field-items">
          <div class="field-item">2008</div>
      </div>
</div>
<div class="prize-fellowship-recipient__body prize-fellowship-recipient__body--default field field-paragraph--field-body field-name-field-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">
    <div class="field-items">
          <div class="field-item"><p>O’Rourke grew up in Brooklyn, where she now lives. After earning her B.A. from Yale University in 1997, she joined&nbsp;<em>The New Yorker</em>&nbsp;as an editorial assistant and became an editor there in 2000. In 2005 she was named poetry co-editor of the&nbsp;<em>Paris Review</em>. She is the 2005 recipient of the Union League Civil and Arts Award. Her poetry and prose have appeared in&nbsp;<em>The New Yorker</em>,&nbsp;<em>The New Republic</em>,&nbsp;<em>Kenyon Review</em>,&nbsp;<em>Poetry</em>,&nbsp;<em>The New York Times Book Review</em>, and elsewhere. Her first book of poems,&nbsp;<em>Halflife</em>, was published by W. W. Norton in 2007.</p>
<p><a href="/news/young-poets-recognized-american-academy-arts-sciences-five-receive-academy-prize-honor-may">Award press release.</a></p>
